SIMPLE: messenger
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Messenger
<hw>Mes"sen*ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>messager</ets>, OF. <ets>messagier</ets>, F. <ets>messager</ets>.
See <er>Message</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who bears a message;
the bearer of a verbal or written communication, notice, or invitation,
from one person to another, or to a public body; specifically, an office
servant who bears messages.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, foreshows, or
foretells.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yon gray lines⟦br⟧
That fret the clouds are <qex>messengers</qex> of day.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A hawser passed round the
capstan, and having its two ends lashed together to form an endless rope
or chain; -- formerly used for heaving in the cable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A person appointed to perform
certain ministerial duties under bankrupt and insolvent laws, such as to
take charge of the estate of the bankrupt or insolvent.</def>
<rj><au>Bouvier. Tomlins.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Carrier; intelligencer; courier; harbinger;
forerunner; precursor; herald.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Messenger bird</b></col>, <cd>the secretary bird, from
its swiftness.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Messet</ent>⟦br⟧
